# Anomaly detection using k-NN

## Introduction
[**Anomaly detection**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anomaly_detection) (also **outlier detection**) deals with identifying unlikely and rare events, which raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data. Several anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature. [**_k_-NN**](http://www.machinelearning.ru/wiki/index.php?title=KNN) (**k nearest neighbors**) is one of the most popular. In this work we will analyse anomalies using _k_-NN. It is method in machine learning that classifies a data point based on assessing the similarity of objects: the classified object belongs to the class to which the objects of the training sample closest to it belong. _k_-NN is not limited to simply predicting values of data points. It can also be used in anomaly detection. As _k_-NN uses underlying patterns in the data to make predictions, any errors in these predictions signal about data points which do not conform to overall trends. Thus, according to this approach the algorithm can be used to detect anomalies.

Now let's view the algorithm for _k_-NN and its application to outlier observation.

## Algorithm
Let us suppose that a training sample is given:
$$X^m=\{(x_1, y_1), .., (x_m, y_m)\}.$$
As a distance function $\rho{(x, x')}$ between object we will take [Euclidian distance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_distance).

For an arbitrary object $u$ we arrange k nearest objects of the training sample $x_i$ in the order of increasing distances to $u$:
$$\rho{(u, x_{1u})} \leq \rho{(u, x_{2u})} \leq ... \leq \rho{(u, x_{ku})} ,$$ where $x_{iu}$ - is the object of the training sample, which is the i-th neighbor of the object $u$. Thus, an arbitrary object $u$ generates renumbering of the sample. In its most general form, the nearest neighbor algorithm is:
$$ f(u) = \argmax_{y\in Y} \sum_{i=1}^m{\{\{y(x_{iu})=y\}*w(i,u)\}},$$ where $w(i, u) = [i \leq k ]$ --- weighting function, which evaluate importance of $i$-th neighbor for classification of object $u$.

The distance to the [_k_-th nearest neighbor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-nearest_neighbors_algorithm) can be seen as an estimation of local density and thus is an outlier score in anomaly detection. The larger the distance to the _k_-NN, the lower the local density, the more likely the query point is an outlier. Thus, three _k_-NN detectors are supported:

- **largest**: use the distance to the kth neighbor as the outlier score
- **mean**: use the average of all k neighbors as the outlier score
- **median**: use the median of the distance to k neighbors as the outlier score

In our case the largest distance is chosen as a value that should be considered by treshold value to consider a datapoint inlier or outlier.

## Example
Here the example of anomaly detection is shown. For that purpose we will generate random dataset with outliers. In our experiment we utilize a Python library called [`PyOD`](https://pyod.readthedocs.io/en/latest/). It allows to create dataset with outliers and detect anomalies using chosen method.

The generated data contains true oulier and true inlier values, inliers are labeled as 0 and outliers are labeled as 1. The synthesized data is generated by this way: normal data is generated by a multivariate Gaussian distribution and outliers are generated by a uniform distribution. The example of generated data is shown below:

![](data:image/png;base64,)
Now let's try to detect anomalies using PyOD.
[![Open In Colab](https://colab.research.google.com/assets/colab-badge.svg#button,,)](https://colab.research.google.com/drive/13btYfHh2rwxpUH-vs12zO72SSL75KzTv)

There are two parameters that we should determine for `kNN()`:

-   **contamination** - the amount of anomalies in the data (in percentage)
-   **n_neighbors** - number of neighbors to consider for measuring the proximity

In order to find outliers we will fit the data to _k_-NN model and, then, see how it is detecting outliers:

![](data:image/png;base64,)
On the picture you can see the following:

- white dots --- real inliners
- black dots --- real outliners
- red contour line shows where anomaly score is equal to threshold

It is obvious from the decision function that  `kNN()` model was good on the training data and all anomalies were detected. However, to determine the real accuracy, let' look at the discrepancies and at the same time how they depend on the number of neighbors.

For identifying an appropriate value for parameter that shows amount of nearest neighbors, we calculate the quantity of differences between training data and predictions by changing **n_neighbors** parameter in `kNN()` in range of 1..20. The following graph represents dependence of accuracy on the number of neighbors.

![](data:image/png;base64,)
We got the best number of nearest neighbors, it is **2**.

As synthesized data is generated randomly, let's build an average graph of precision and the number of neighbors dependency for 20 starts.

![](data:image/png;base64,)
As we can see, we got the same value for the best amount of nearest neighbors.
